    "what_description": "Ceropegia molaventi is a species of flowering plant in the family Apocynaceae, native to the Western Ghats of India. It is a perennial climber with woody stems, 1.5-3.5 meters long, that are hairy and glabrescent towards the apex, with leaves that are ovate-lanceolate, 10-15 cm long, and 5-7 cm wide, with a petiole 2-3 cm long. The inflorescence is a corymb, with flowers that are white, 2.5-3 cm long, and 1.5-2 cm wide, with a hairy calyx, and a corolla with five lobes. The flowers are pollinated by moths, specifically the hawk moths, which are attracted to the strong, sweet fragrance and nectar-rich flowers. The plant is epiphytic, growing on trees and rocks, and is found in dry deciduous forests at elevations of 400-600 meters above sea level.",
